<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-09-05T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-09-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="84" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d84">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 <gloss target="#t_EW1">EW</gloss>/9–444</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The President’s Special Assistant</hi>
                                    (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Hopkins</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-09-05">September 5,
                                        1944</date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: With minor
                                reservations about language which do not affect the intent of the
                                document, “Suggested Recommendations on Treatment of Germany from
                                the Cabinet Committee for the President”,<note n="1" xml:id="d84fn1"><hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_95">p.
                                        95</ref>.</note> I approve of it.</p>
                            <p>If there be agreement on policies, then it becomes of the utmost
                                importance for the proper Government Officials to indicate how the
                                policies in this document are to be implemented.</p>
                            <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Harry L.
                                Hopkins</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>